Sure! Here's an example of a for loop in Java:

```java
for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println("Count: " + i);
}
```
This loop will iterate 5 times, and each time it will print the value of `i` to the console. The loop starts with `i` set to 1 and continues until `i` is less than or equal to 5. After each iteration, `i` is incremented by 1.

To generate random numbers in Java, you can use the `java.util.Random` class. Here's an example of how to generate a random number:

```java
import java.util.Random;

public class RandomNumberExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Random random = new Random();
        int randomNumber = random.nextInt(); // Generates a random integer

        System.out.println("Random Number: " + randomNumber);
    }
}
```
In the above example, we first create an instance of the `Random` class. Then, we use the `nextInt()` method to get a random integer. The `nextInt()` method can optionally take an argument specifying the upper bound of the random number. If you want a random number within a specific range, you can use `random.nextInt(max)`, where `max` is the upper bound (exclusive).

Remember to import the `java.util.Random` class at the beginning of your Java file.

Certainly! Here's an example of a `switch` statement with the `when` keyword, which was introduced in Java 14:

```java
public class DayOfWeekExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int dayOfWeek = 3;

        switch (dayOfWeek) {
            case 1 -> System.out.println("Monday");
            case 2 -> System.out.println("Tuesday");
            case 3 -> System.out.println("Wednesday");
            case 4, 5 -> System.out.println("Thursday or Friday");
            default -> System.out.println("Weekend day");
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, we have a variable `dayOfWeek` indicating the current day. The `switch` statement uses the `when` keyword to match the value of `dayOfWeek` with different cases.

Based on the value of `dayOfWeek`, the corresponding case will be executed, printing the respective day of the week. If none of the specified cases match, the `default` case will be executed, indicating a weekend day.

In Java, you cannot directly use a range in a `switch` statement. Unlike some other programming languages, Java `switch` statements only support discrete values, not ranges.

However, you can achieve similar functionality by using multiple cases together. Here's an example of how you can handle a range in a `switch` statement:

```java
public class NumberRangeExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int number = 10;

        switch (number) {
            case 1, 2, 3, 4, 5:
                System.out.println("Number is in the range 1-5");
                break;
            case 6, 7, 8, 9, 10:
                System.out.println("Number is in the range 6-10");
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Number is outside the specified ranges");
                break;
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `switch` statement checks the value of the `number` variable. If the number matches any of the cases specified for each range, the corresponding code block will be executed. You can list multiple cases together in a comma-separated format to define a range-like behavior within the `switch` statement.
